{
  "text": "Although our approach proved successful, there are still several areas that can be largely improved with future works. First, one key issue, outlined by the real experiments, is the need for force estimation. Related to this, we outlined the need for distributed force sensing on the entire robot body, instead of only on the wrist. Distributed tactile sensors can improve body grasps as tested with the HRP-2 in [CITATION_1] . Another key improvement concerns the wrench prediction model for better proactive behaviors. A current limitation is that the wrench is simply predicted to be constant over the preview horizon. However, since we believe that the framework is very well suited for including proactivity, a better perceptual model is necessary. This requires integrating human perception for intention recognition, a difficult challenge, but also an active research area in physical human-robot interaction. Methods combining machine learning and dynamical systems, e.g., [CITATION_2] could be investigated as they could also encompass the planning part.",
